<div id="review_475327830" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/475327830" />
    <a title="Stephen Durrant" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1457001-stephen-durrant"><img alt="Stephen Durrant" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1362701086p2/1457001.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/475327830?book_show_action=true">Dec 11, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephen Durrant" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephen Durrant" href="/user/show/1457001-stephen-durrant">Stephen Durrant</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9782877068161" href="/book/show/16033842-la-v-rit-sur-l-affaire-harry-quebert">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer475327830" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11362399276160655459">Joel Dicker is a 27-year-old Swiss writer whose &quot;La Vérité sur L&apos;Affaire Harry Quebert&quot; has recently won two prestigious literary prizes and become a bestseller here in France. Its success, I think, results from being a complex and engrossing piece of detective fiction, involving novelists no less, and being set in America, where, according to the book jacket, Dicker has traveled extensively. The story concerns the discovery of the body of a fifteen-year old girl who disappeared thirty years ear</span>
  <span id="freeText11362399276160655459" style="display:none">Joel Dicker is a 27-year-old Swiss writer whose "La Vérité sur L'Affaire Harry Quebert" has recently won two prestigious literary prizes and become a bestseller here in France. Its success, I think, results from being a complex and engrossing piece of detective fiction, involving novelists no less, and being set in America, where, according to the book jacket, Dicker has traveled extensively. The story concerns the discovery of the body of a fifteen-year old girl who disappeared thirty years earlier under strange circumstances that point toward the likelihood she had been murdered. Items found with her body lead to the arrest of Harry Quebert, a famous novelist. One of Quebert's former students, Marcus Goldman, a budding novelist himself (novelists like to imagine that novelists are especially interesting), takes it upon himself to prove his teacher innocent. What follows is a 600-page roller coaster ride with more twists and turns than Steel Dragon 2000 and Millennium Force put together. The ride is so much fun that one almost forgets how implausible and problematic much of it is. The major implausibility (and there are others) is that the police would allow a young novelist into the very center of an on-going homicide investigation--indeed allow him virtually to lead that investigation. Now, I know that most detective fiction demands some "willing suspension of disbelief," to use Coleridge's term, but that too often becomes difficult in this particular case. Also, no one should be surprised when a writer describing what for him is a foreign country falls into comfortable stereotypes. After all, stereotypes, however much we might be inclined to deny it, frequently have some basis and it does give almost everyone a feeling of glee when they see behavior that confirms what they "always knew." Human enough. But several of the stereotypes in this novel go a bit far. Marcus' mother is such an overdrawn stereotype of the Jewish mother and Tamara Quinn of a ditsy small-town woman that we begin to feel we have wandered into a Monty Python movie rather than a work of gritty detective fiction. All that being said, one does read on . . . and on, almost compulsively, wondering how it will all end. And like with a good roller coaster ride, one comes away dizzy, mildly satisfied and not entirely sure one would do it again. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11362399276160655459" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

